Hereâs the regression from last week.

mod1 <- lm(score ~ bty,
           data = d)

get_regression_table(mod1)
# A tibble: 2 Ã 7
  term      estimate std_error statistic p_value lower_ci upper_ci
  <chr>        <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>   <dbl>    <dbl>    <dbl>
1 intercept    3.88      0.076     51.0        0    3.73     4.03 
2 bty          0.067     0.016      4.09       0    0.035    0.099

Note: When beauty (x) is 0, we expect a person to get a teaching evaluation of 3.88. This has no substantive value because beauty will never be 0. However, it is worth noting that this is what the numerical values indicate. Note also that every time we move 1 beauty point to the right, we can expect the teaching evaluation to go up by .067.

Letâs look at the predictions and residuals.

mod1_preds <- get_regression_points(mod1) #regression model 1 predictions

Hereâs the regression line (blue).

`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Here are the residuals.

Note: The y-axis is no longer score; the y-axis is now our guess. Moreover, the residual plot can reveal the wrong model type (i.e., data follows a parabola but you used lm).

One way to quantify how well a predictor predicts the outcome is to use the variance. Weâve seen this already but letâs review. Hereâs the formula. \(\bar{y}\) is the mean of \(y\).

\[ V(y) = \frac{1}{n-1}\sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i - \bar{y})^2 \]

Note: Equation above is basically the average squared distance from the observation to the mean.

Since our outcome is evaluation score, we can just do that.

var_y <- d |> 
  pull(score) |> 
  var()

var_y
[1] 0.2957886

Note: We are only using the scores here; we are not using beauty at all. We are looking to understand the variance that exists in the first place among course evaluations. (âsome do, some donâtâ)

This is equivalent to the variance of the âresidualsâ when we just guess the mean value for every person!

Note: Can guess the average for everyone. OR, if I knew the beauty score, maybe I could improve my guess of evaluations.

Adding beauty as a predictor improves our guess.

`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Note: In this dataset, using other information will always improve your guess in the sample. However, it is also kind of cheating, because we are using our sample to predict our sample.

Now letâs see what the spread looks like if we look at the residuals from the regression line.

var_yhat1 <- mod1_preds |> 
  pull(residual) |> 
  var()

var_yhat1
[1] 0.2854513

Note: variance went down a little when account for beauty (from .29 to .28). Also, (.29-.28)/.29 = 3.5%, meaning beauty explains 3.5% of the variance. Takeaway: we make better guesses when we use other information. Also, even small values can be significant (these are called âmarginal gainsâ in the sports realms).

If we take the ratio of these and subtract it from one, that gives us the \(R^2\) or âproportion of variance explainedâ by beauty scores.

1 - (var_yhat1 / var_y)
[1] 0.03494822

It looks like âbeautyâ can account for about 3.5 percent of the variance in the evaluation scores.

In other words, if we try to guess instructorsâ evaluation scores, our guesses will be 3.5 percent less wrong on average if we know the instructorâs beauty rating.

We can get this from broom::glance() or moderndive::get_regression_summaries() without doing it manually. The latter will be a more curated list of things youâll need for this course.

broom::glance(mod1)
# A tibble: 1 Ã 12

      <dbl>         <dbl> <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl> <dbl>  <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
1    0.0350        0.0329 0.535      16.7 0.0000508     1  -366.  738.  751.
# â¹ 3 more variables: deviance <dbl>, df.residual <int>, nobs <int>
moderndive::get_regression_summaries(mod1)
# A tibble: 1 Ã 9
  r_squared adj_r_squared   mse  rmse sigma statistic p_value    df  nobs
      <dbl>         <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>     <dbl>   <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
1     0.035         0.033 0.285 0.534 0.535      16.7       0     1   463

Note: If we want to know the maximum difference beauty could make between the prettiest and ugliest instructor, we could run: max(d$bty).067 - min(d$bty).067 in the console (= .435). In other words, the model thinks the biggest difference that beauty could make is .435 points on a 10-point scale.

Looks like male instructors get slightly better evaluations but this only accounts for a tiny bit of the of the variance. Donât be confused however: small amounts of variance can be really important even if they donât tell the whole story of variability.

In general, we are not going to want to do this with different variables one by one. We want to do multiple regression.

mod3 <- lm(score ~ bty + sex,
           data = d)

get_regression_table(mod3)
# A tibble: 3 Ã 7
  term      estimate std_error statistic p_value lower_ci upper_ci
  <chr>        <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>   <dbl>    <dbl>    <dbl>
1 intercept    3.75      0.085     44.3    0        3.58     3.91 
2 bty          0.074     0.016      4.56   0        0.042    0.106
3 sex: male    0.172     0.05       3.43   0.001    0.074    0.271

Hereâs what this model does.

Hereâs the formula:

\[ \widehat{score}_i = 3.75 + .074(beauty_i) + .172(male_i) \]

We might instead prefer a model like this, which allows the relationship between beauty and evaluations to be different for male and female instructors.

`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Hereâs the syntax, results, and formula.

mod4 <- lm(score ~ bty + sex + bty:sex,
           data = d)

get_regression_table(mod4)
# A tibble: 4 Ã 7
  term        estimate std_error statistic p_value lower_ci upper_ci
  <chr>          <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>   <dbl>    <dbl>    <dbl>
1 intercept      3.95      0.118     33.5    0        3.72     4.18 
2 bty            0.031     0.024      1.28   0.202   -0.017    0.078
3 sex: male     -0.184     0.153     -1.20   0.232   -0.485    0.118
4 bty:sexmale    0.08      0.032      2.45   0.015    0.016    0.143

\[ \widehat{score}_i = 3.95 + .031(beauty_i) + -.184(male_i) + .080(beauty_i \times male_i) \] The slope for female instructors is .031. The slope for male instructors is .031 + .080 = .111.
